[49m[38;5;10m+     50[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     51[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## The Technology: Conversational Clinical-Trial Recruitment Grounded in IRB-Approved Materials, Pre-Screening, and Coordinator Handoff
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     52[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     53[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Why Clinical-Trial Recruitment Has Resisted Digital Tools, and Why The Latest Attempts Are Different
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     54[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     55[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Clinical-trial recruitment, as a workflow, has been a labor-intensive, coordinator-driven process for almost all of its history. The reason is structural. Eligibility evaluation against a trial protocol is a domain-specific, often-amended, sometimes-contradictory set of criteria that requires careful interpretation against the candidate's actual clinical state, with judgment calls about how to handle ambiguous data, missing data, and edge cases. The candidate-coordinator conversation is a relationship-and-trust-building interaction in which the coordinator answers questions, builds the candidate's understanding of the trial, identifies concerns, and supports the candidate through a complex decision. The consent process is, by design, a deliberate slowing-down where the candidate has time and space to consider the trial. Each of these layers requires human judgment, human relationship, and human pace.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     56[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     57[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Digital tools have, for most of the field's history, been able to support some pieces of this workflow and not others. Trial-registry websites (ClinicalTrials.gov is the dominant U.S. example) provide a searchable index of active trials with criteria, sponsor, location, and contact information. EHR-based screening tools run patients in the institutional record against trial criteria using structured data, often producing high false-positive rates and requiring coordinator review. Patient-facing search tools attempt to bridge the registry's clinician-language to patient-language, with mixed success. None of these tools can engage the candidate in conversation, can answer the candidate's questions in plain language, can adapt to what the candidate already knows and what they need explained, can run the pre-screening interactively, and can support the warm handoff to the coordinator. The activation-energy gate that loses Maria in the kitchen-table scene above is what these tools have not been able to address.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     58[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     59[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The thing that changed the workflow shape is the same thing that changed the workflow shape for the previous chapter 11 recipes: large language models that can carry on a coherent, sustained, plain-language conversation, deployed as tool-using LLMs with action surfaces that retrieve trial-specific content, perform structured pre-screening, and route to research coordinators. A conversational tool, deployed with careful institutional governance and IRB approval, can engage the candidate at their preferred reading level in their preferred language, can explain the trial without requiring the candidate to read a thousand-word abstract, can run the pre-screening interactively (which produces both higher candidate satisfaction and higher data quality than a static form), can answer follow-up questions grounded in IRB-approved materials, and can route the interested-and-potentially-eligible candidate to a research coordinator with full conversation context attached. The bot is not a coordinator. The bot is a tool that lowers the activation energy for the candidate to engage with a trial, raises the quality of the candidates who reach the coordinator, and meaningfully expands the candidate pool's diversity by removing structural barriers (language, reading level, channel preference, time-of-day availability) that have historically gated trial engagement.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     60[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     61[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The architectural shift is from "static registry the candidate searches" to "conversational interface that engages the candidate, runs pre-screening, and routes to coordinators." The bot's value is concentrated in five places: the lower activation-energy access (the candidate who would not call the study-coordinator phone number will, sometimes, type into a chat), the plain-language explanation grounded in IRB-approved materials (the candidate gets the protocol's actual content explained at their reading level), the interactive pre-screening (which produces higher candidate engagement and lower coordinator workload than static forms), the multilingual and multi-channel reach (which structurally improves diversity), and the warm handoff with full context (which reduces candidate friction and improves coordinator efficiency).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     62[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     63[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A note on what conversational clinical-trial recruitment AI is and is not, because the category is new and is being implemented across a wide range of architectures. The careful end of the spectrum is IRB-approved, protocol-grounded, plain-language candidate engagement with structured pre-screening and warm handoff to research coordinators, deployed under institutional research-operations governance. <!-- TODO: verify; the digital-trial-recruitment landscape has produced a range of platforms including TrialSpark, Antidote, Deep 6 AI, Mendel, and others; specific product positioning and evidence varies --> The middle of the spectrum is general-purpose conversational AI used by patients to ask questions about clinical trials in general. The risky end of the spectrum is bot-mediated recruitment that pressures candidates, presents one-sided trial benefits, blurs the bot's role with the consent process, or operates without IRB approval. This recipe is firmly in the careful end. The architectural decisions are, in part, decisions about which end of the spectrum the product lives on.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     64[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     65[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### What a Clinical-Trial Recruitment Bot Actually Does
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     66[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     67[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A clinical-trial recruitment bot, as designed in this recipe, is a tool-using LLM with a system prompt that tells it which assistant it is, the candidate's authenticated context (where the candidate has been pre-identified by the institution and is engaging through an authenticated channel), the active trial portfolio with per-trial IRB-approved candidate-facing materials, the per-trial pre-screening question sets, and a careful set of tools for retrieving trial content, running pre-screening, surfacing trial logistics, routing to research coordinators, and logging events for IRB and operational audit.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     68[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     69[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The conversation surface is not one conversation. It is a stream of conversational episodes, sometimes initiated by the candidate (responding to a recruitment outreach, finding the bot through a registry-and-bot integration, arriving from a clinician referral), sometimes initiated by the institution (a candidate identified via chart-review screening receives a bot-introduction outreach with their consent), sometimes initiated by an existing patient asking their care team about trial options (the bot is a tool the care team uses to explore options with the patient).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     70[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     71[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The bot's task surface decomposes roughly as follows.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     72[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     73[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Candidate entry and disclosure.** The candidate enters through one of several channels: an authenticated patient-portal channel (the candidate is an existing patient at the institution, has logged in, and is engaging with a trial-recruitment conversation initiated by their care team or by an institutional outreach); an unauthenticated public channel (the candidate finds the bot through a public-facing trial-recruitment website or a registry-and-bot integration); a clinician-referral channel (the candidate's clinician has handed them a link or a code to engage the bot for a specific trial); a study-team-direct channel (a research coordinator has invited the candidate to the bot for pre-screening before a phone call). Each channel has different authentication, different consent, and different permitted scope.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     74[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     75[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The first conversation does the disclosure work that is non-negotiable in trial-recruitment AI: the bot identifies itself as a chat tool and not a person, explains that it is a candidate-engagement tool and not a substitute for the formal consent process or for the research coordinator, names the IRB approval under which the recruitment communication is being conducted (with IRB number where appropriate), describes the privacy posture in plain language with explicit attention to how recruitment-conversation data is used and retained, names the candidate's right to stop the conversation at any time and to be removed from outreach, and (in unauthenticated channels) explains what data the bot is collecting and how it will be used. The candidate acknowledges. As with the mental-health recipe, this is not boilerplate; it is an architectural decision with regulatory and ethical consequences if treated as boilerplate.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     76[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     77[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Trial introduction in plain language.** The bot introduces the candidate to the specific trial (or to a small set of trials filtered by the candidate's stated condition), with content drawn from the IRB-approved candidate-facing materials. The introduction is at the candidate's stated reading level (typically 6th-to-8th-grade reading level for the default; configurable per trial and per candidate cohort), in the candidate's stated language, with the trial's purpose, the population it is studying, the interventions being compared, the time commitment, the visit schedule, the kinds of risks and the kinds of potential benefits, the alternatives (standard of care, no treatment, other trials), and the basic logistics (where, how often, what is paid for) presented in balanced, neutral language. The bot does not enthuse about the trial. The bot does not minimize risks. The bot does not pressure the candidate.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     78[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     79[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Eligibility pre-screening with IRB-approved question sets.** The bot runs through the trial's pre-screening questions in conversational form. The questions are an IRB-approved subset of the protocol's eligibility criteria, written in plain language, with the data-handling and the data-use explained at each step. Pre-screening covers categorical inclusion criteria (does the candidate have the condition the trial is studying), categorical exclusion criteria (does the candidate have characteristics that would exclude them), and (where the candidate consents and the institution permits) chart-context confirmation (the bot's pre-screening can be supplemented by chart-context retrieval where the candidate is an existing patient with consent). The pre-screening is interactive: the candidate can ask follow-up questions about why a question is being asked, can decline to answer specific questions, and can request to talk to a person at any time. The pre-screening does not produce an enrollment decision. The pre-screening produces a "appears potentially eligible" or "appears not eligible" or "needs coordinator review" determination. The determination is non-binding; the formal eligibility evaluation is done by the research coordinator and (where applicable) the principal investigator.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     80[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     81[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Question-and-answer about the trial, grounded in IRB-approved materials.** The candidate asks questions: "what does the time commitment look like?" "will this affect my insurance?" "what happens if I stop participating?" "are there other trials I should consider?" "is this a placebo-controlled trial?" "will I have access to the experimental drug after the trial ends?" The bot answers grounded in IRB-approved candidate-facing materials, with citations. Where the question is outside the IRB-approved candidate-facing materials, the bot explicitly defers to the research coordinator.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     82[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     83[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Interest assessment with neutral framing.** After the introduction, the pre-screening, and the question-and-answer, the bot assesses candidate interest with neutral framing: "Based on what we have talked about, would you like me to connect you with a research coordinator who can answer more questions, walk through the formal consent process if you decide to go further, and help you with next steps?" The candidate can say yes, no, or "let me think about it." Each response is recorded with appropriate audit. A "no" or "let me think about it" response is not a closed door; the candidate can return at any time, and the bot does not pressure or follow up unless the candidate has consented to follow-up outreach.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     84[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     85[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Warm handoff to the research coordinator (for interested-and-potentially-eligible candidates).** The bot routes the candidate to the appropriate research coordinator for the trial with the conversation context attached, the pre-screening outcome attached (with appropriate caveats about non-binding nature), and the candidate's stated preferences attached (preferred language, preferred contact method, preferred contact times). The handoff is warm: the coordinator gets the conversation context, the candidate does not have to start over. Where the institution operates synchronous-handoff (the coordinator is reachable in the moment), the bot bridges to the coordinator via chat, voice, or video. Where the institution operates asynchronous-handoff, the bot tells the candidate when to expect coordinator contact and what the next steps look like.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     86[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     87[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Care-team coordination (with consent).** Where the candidate has consented to clinician notification, the bot notifies the candidate's treating clinician of the trial-engagement conversation with a structured summary, supporting the clinician's involvement in the candidate's enrollment decision and operational care coordination if enrollment proceeds.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     88[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     89[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Audit and IRB reporting.** Every recruitment conversation generates a durable audit record: the channel, the authentication context, the IRB-approved version of the recruitment materials and the pre-screening question set, the conversation transcript, the pre-screening outcome, the candidate's interest assessment, the handoff disposition, and the IRB-relevant events (e.g., adverse-event-style reports if the recruitment communication produces an unexpected event). The audit record supports the institution's IRB obligations, FDA obligations where applicable, HIPAA obligations, and the institutional research-operations metrics.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     90[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     91[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Follow-up management with consent.** Where the candidate has consented to follow-up, the bot can re-engage at the candidate's stated cadence (e.g., "I'd like a week to think about it; can you check back next week?"). The follow-up is consent-gated, time-limited, and clearly labeled.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     92[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     93[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Multi-trial portfolio routing.** Most institutions have multiple active trials. The bot can introduce the candidate to a small set of trials filtered by the candidate's stated condition and characteristics, can run pre-screening for the trial of interest, and can support cross-trial questions ("if I am not eligible for this trial, are there other trials I should consider?") with appropriate fairness in trial presentation.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     94[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     95[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Why a Generic LLM Cannot Run a Clinical-Trial Recruitment Bot
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     96[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     97[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A naive product approach would be: take a generalist LLM, give it a chat surface, prompt it with "you are a clinical-trial recruitment assistant," provide it with a public-facing trial description, and let it engage with potential candidates. This breaks in several specific ways, each of which has IRB, regulatory, ethical, and operational consequences.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     98[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     99[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no IRB-approved-materials grounding.** Patient-facing recruitment communication is reviewed and approved by the IRB. A generalist LLM that paraphrases or summarizes the trial description is producing recruitment communication that has not been IRB-approved, which is a regulatory non-starter. The architectural answer is strict citation grounding: the bot delivers content drawn from IRB-approved candidate-facing materials, and the bot's answers cite the specific IRB-approved source.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    100[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    101[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no pre-screening discipline.** Eligibility pre-screening against a protocol's criteria is detailed work. A generalist LLM that attempts to interpret eligibility criteria from a free-text protocol description will produce inconsistent results. The architectural answer is structured pre-screening: the institution defines, with the principal investigator's review and the IRB's approval, a plain-language pre-screening question set with explicit decision rules; the bot runs the pre-screening as a structured tool, not as a freestyle interpretation.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    102[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    103[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no consent-process scope discipline.** Informed consent is a regulated, deliberate process conducted by humans with the candidate, with specific elements required by FDA and the Common Rule. <!-- TODO: verify; informed-consent requirements for clinical research are specified in 21 CFR 50.25 and 45 CFR 46.116, with specific required elements; specific obligations vary by trial type --> A generalist LLM that drifts toward consent-process language is operating outside the bot's scope. The architectural answer is explicit consent-process exclusion: the bot's prompt forbids consent delivery, the output safety detects consent-process drift, and the bot routes consent questions to the research coordinator.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    104[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    105[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no balanced-presentation discipline.** Trial-recruitment communication has specific requirements about balanced presentation of risks, benefits, and alternatives. A generalist LLM, prompted to be helpful, may produce one-sided or persuasive content. The architectural answer is explicit balanced-presentation discipline encoded in the IRB-approved candidate-facing materials, the system prompt, and the output-safety review.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    106[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    107[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of when not to engage.** Some questions are outside the bot's scope. A request for medical advice ("should I do this trial or take the standard chemotherapy?"), a request for financial advice ("will my insurance cover this?" — partially yes, but with limits), a request for legal advice, a request to discuss other patients' experiences (which the bot does not have access to and should not invent), a request to commit to enrollment ("I want to enroll, sign me up"): each is outside scope. The bot recognizes the boundary and routes; the generalist LLM tries to be helpful and crosses the boundary.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    108[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    109[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model invents trial details when grounding is weak.** A bot freestyling the trial visit schedule, the time commitment, the inclusion criteria, the exclusion criteria, or any other operational detail is producing recruitment communication that has not been IRB-approved and may be wrong. The architectural answer is strict citation grounding to IRB-approved candidate-facing materials, with regenerate-or-defer as the response when grounding is weak.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    110[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    111[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of the candidate's vulnerability.** Many candidates are facing serious diagnoses (cancer, neurodegenerative disease, rare disease, mental-health conditions). The candidate is, by definition, in a position of medical vulnerability. The bot's tone is calibrated for this: not enthusiastic, not pressuring, not minimizing the seriousness of the candidate's situation, not implying that the trial is a sure path to benefit. The architectural answer is tone calibration in the system prompt and output-safety review, with explicit forbidden patterns (pressure, persuasion, minimization, false reassurance).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    112[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    113[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of equipoise.** Clinical equipoise (the principle that a trial is ethical to conduct only when there is genuine uncertainty about which arm is better) is a core research-ethics concept. <!-- TODO: verify; clinical equipoise is a foundational concept in research ethics with extensive bioethics literature; specific operational interpretation varies --> The bot's recruitment communication does not imply that the experimental arm is better than the control arm or vice versa; the bot describes both arms in balanced terms.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    114[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    115[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of mandatory IRB amendments.** When the protocol changes, the candidate-facing materials must be re-reviewed and re-approved by the IRB. The bot's content library is versioned, IRB-approval-stamped, and updated only on IRB approval. The architectural answer is governance: the candidate-facing-materials library is a versioned asset with named ownership at the institutional research-operations team and IRB-approval gating on updates.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    116[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    117[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of FDA advertising guidance.** FDA has specific guidance on advertising for FDA-regulated clinical investigations. <!-- TODO: verify; FDA guidance on recruiting study subjects includes the FDA Information Sheet "Recruiting Study Subjects" and related guidance documents; specific obligations vary by trial type and regulatory framework --> Recruitment language must comply. The architectural answer is institutional regulatory team review of the recruitment-communication corpus, with FDA-experienced regulatory counsel involvement where the trial is FDA-regulated.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    118[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    119[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of the Tuskegee legacy and trust.** Clinical-trial recruitment in the U.S. operates against a backdrop of historical injustices in research, particularly affecting Black and Indigenous patients, that have produced legitimate, well-grounded distrust of research in these communities. <!-- TODO: verify; the historical record of research injustices in the U.S. includes the Tuskegee syphilis study, the Henrietta Lacks case, research on incarcerated populations, and others; the impact on contemporary patient trust in research is documented in extensive literature --> A bot that ignores this context is not engaging the population it should be reaching. The architectural answer is community-engagement-informed recruitment design, content review by community advisors, transparency about institutional research practices, and explicit candidate-rights communication.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    120[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    121[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of compensation conversations.** Many trials offer compensation for participation (visit-related travel, time, in some cases lost wages). FDA, IRB, and the OHRP have specific guidance on compensation framing to avoid undue influence. <!-- TODO: verify; FDA, OHRP, and IRB guidance on participant compensation distinguishes reimbursement for expenses, compensation for time, and incentives that could constitute undue influence --> The bot's compensation conversation is IRB-approved, balanced, and avoids implying that the compensation is the reason to enroll.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    122[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    123[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has compliance implications specific to research conduct.** The conversation contains PHI (the candidate's diagnoses, characteristics, and screening responses) and research-conduct data (which trials were presented, which pre-screening outcomes were produced, which handoffs were initiated). HIPAA, the Common Rule, FDA regulations where applicable, and state-specific patient-protection statutes apply. <!-- TODO: verify; HIPAA application to clinical-research recruitment includes considerations for "research" use under 45 CFR 164.512(i), authorization requirements, and limited data set provisions; specific obligations vary --> The audit, retention, access-control, and downstream IRB-reporting story handles each.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    124[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    125[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of mandatory adverse-event-style reporting.** If a recruitment conversation produces an unexpected event (a candidate discloses a serious safety concern, a candidate appears to be in crisis, a candidate reports a privacy breach in their care), the institution may have IRB or institutional-policy obligations to report. The bot's pipeline includes structured event-detection and routing.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    126[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    127[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of consent-vs-screening distinction.** The pre-screening conversation that the bot conducts, where the candidate provides eligibility-relevant information, is itself an act that requires consent (because it is a research-related collection of PHI). The institution's HIPAA-Authorization-or-Limited-Data-Set posture for the pre-screening, and the IRB's review of the pre-screening process, are part of the architectural decision. The bot operates within the institution's IRB-approved framework; the bot does not invent its own consent posture.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    128[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    129[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of cross-trial fairness.** The institution may have multiple trials open for similar conditions. The bot's introduction-of-trials process must be fair: the candidate is not steered toward the trial that has the highest sponsor incentive or the easiest enrollment criteria; the candidate is presented with the trials for which they appear potentially eligible based on their characteristics, with balanced presentation. The institutional research-operations team owns the trial-presentation policy.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    130[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    131[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of when to end the conversation.** A candidate who has said "no" deserves a graceful exit, with clear information about how to return if they change their mind, how to be removed from outreach if that is their preference, and how to access the institution's other trial-information resources. The bot's conversation-ending heuristics are reviewed by clinical and IRB leadership.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    132[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    133[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### What the Trial-Recruitment Bot Has To Do That the Previous Bots Did Not
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    134[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    135[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Recipes 11.1 through 11.9 established the patterns this recipe inherits: input safety screening, identity verification, tool-use orchestration, output safety screening, audit logging, scope discipline, prompt-injection defense, graceful degradation, citation grounding, multilingual deployment, per-cohort monitoring, and warm-handoff infrastructure. The trial-recruitment bot adds eight structural commitments those recipes did not have.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    136[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    137[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **IRB-approved-materials grounding as architectural primitive.** Every piece of recruitment communication, every pre-screening question, every plain-language explanation, every answer to a candidate question is grounded in IRB-approved candidate-facing materials. The materials library is versioned, IRB-approval-stamped, and updated only on IRB approval. Citations are preserved on every response.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    138[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    139[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Pre-screening discipline with structured question sets.** Eligibility pre-screening is conducted using IRB-approved structured question sets with explicit decision rules. The pre-screening produces a non-binding "appears potentially eligible" determination; formal eligibility evaluation is done by the research coordinator.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    140[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    141[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Balanced-presentation discipline.** Recruitment communication is balanced: risks and benefits, experimental arm and control arm, the trial and the standard-of-care alternative, the trial and other trials. The system prompt, the IRB-approved materials, and the output-safety review enforce balance. The bot does not enthuse, does not pressure, does not minimize.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    142[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    143[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Consent-process scope exclusion.** The bot does not perform informed consent. Consent is an explicit out-of-scope topic; consent-process drift is detected by output safety; consent questions are routed to the research coordinator.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    144[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    145[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Per-trial governance with IRB-approval lifecycle.** The trial portfolio is a managed asset: trials open, accrue, amend, close. Each amendment is an IRB submission, a content update, and a candidate-experience change. The institutional research-operations team owns the lifecycle.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    146[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    147[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Equity-aware recruitment design.** The bot is deployed with explicit attention to engaging under-represented populations, with multilingual support, multi-channel access, multi-reading-level content, community-engagement-informed design, and per-cohort monitoring of engagement and pre-screening outcomes.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    148[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    149[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Coordinator-handoff infrastructure with workforce capacity sizing.** The research-coordinator workforce is sized to the candidate volume the bot produces, with peak-hour and per-trial coverage. Under-sized capacity produces candidate experience degradation and is an enrollment-pipeline gap.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    150[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    151[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **FDA-strategy alignment for FDA-regulated investigations.** Where the trial is FDA-regulated, the recruitment communication is subject to FDA advertising guidance. The institutional regulatory team is involved in recruitment-corpus review.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    152[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    153[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The rest is largely the same as the previous chapter 11 recipes: tool-surface contract management, conversation logging, scope filtering, per-cohort monitoring, graceful degradation when upstream systems fail.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    154[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    155[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### The Clinical-Trial Recruitment Reality
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    156[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    157[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A few notes on what makes trial recruitment specifically harder than the other chapter 11 use cases.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    158[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    159[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The IRB lifecycle is the operational tempo.** Every change to the bot's recruitment-communication content goes through IRB review and approval. The institutional research-operations team owns this lifecycle. Engineering teams accustomed to "ship and iterate" cycles must adjust to "submit, wait for IRB review, ship-on-approval" cycles, which are typically measured in weeks, not days.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    160[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    161[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The candidate population is not representative of the general patient population.** Candidates engaging with the bot are responding to specific recruitment outreach for specific trials. The candidate pool is shaped by the outreach channels, the trial-fit-with-population, and the institutional patient mix. Equity-aware recruitment design counters the structural biases that have historically produced under-represented research populations.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    162[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    163[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The relationship is shorter than chronic-disease coaching or mental-health support.** A trial-recruitment conversation may be one session, may extend to a few sessions if the candidate takes time to think about it, but is not a long-running relationship. The bot's value is concentrated in a narrow time window. Engagement attrition is less central than in the other recipes; the central operational risk is candidate fall-off between the bot's conversation and the coordinator's first contact.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    164[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    165[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The candidate's medical situation is often serious.** Candidates in oncology trials, in rare-disease trials, in advanced-cardiovascular trials, in neurodegenerative trials are often facing significant medical situations. The bot's tone is calibrated for this; the candidate is treated with the gravity their situation deserves, and the bot does not over-promise or pressure.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    166[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    167[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The trial sponsor's commercial interest is structurally present.** Many trials are sponsored by drug or device manufacturers with commercial interests in enrollment outcomes. The institution's IRB and regulatory framework enforce balanced communication; the bot operates within that framework. Engineering teams should be aware that the institutional governance is the protection against sponsor pressure to bias the bot's communication.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    168[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    169[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The institutional research-operations team is the operational owner.** The bot is not owned by clinical-care operations; it is owned by research operations, with clinical-leadership input. The institutional structure is different.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    170[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    171[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Multi-language deployment is structurally important and operationally complex.** Trials that recruit primarily in English produce study populations that under-represent non-English-speaking patients. Multi-language deployment requires per-language IRB-approved candidate-facing-materials translations (not just translation, but IRB-approval of the translation), per-language pre-screening question sets, per-language tone calibration, and per-language equity monitoring.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    172[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    173[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Adolescent and pediatric considerations are out-of-scope without specific design.** Trial recruitment for minors involves parental consent (or assent depending on age and jurisdiction), specific IRB requirements, COPPA compliance for online interactions, and a different communication framework. <!-- TODO: verify; pediatric clinical-trial recruitment considerations include 21 CFR 50 Subpart D for FDA-regulated pediatric research, 45 CFR 46 Subpart D for HHS-funded pediatric research, COPPA application to online recruitment of minors, and IRB-specific requirements --> Most adult-deployment products explicitly exclude minors.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    174[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    175[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Rare-disease and oncology trials have specific recruitment dynamics.** Rare-disease trials may have small, geographically dispersed candidate pools where the bot's role is amplified. Oncology trials often involve candidates who have already exhausted standard-of-care options and are looking at trials as a last-line option, with specific emotional dynamics. Per-trial recruitment design accounts for these.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    176[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    177[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Compensation framing has specific regulatory considerations.** FDA, OHRP, and IRB guidance distinguish reimbursement for expenses, compensation for time, and incentives that could constitute undue influence. The bot's discussion of compensation is IRB-approved and balanced.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    178[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    179[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Liability exposure is meaningfully present.** A bot that misrepresents trial details, that drifts into consent territory, that pressures candidates, or that mishandles sensitive disclosures (e.g., a candidate discloses suicidal ideation during a recruitment conversation for a depression trial) is producing institutional liability. Mitigation: IRB approval as the architectural floor; output-safety with consent-process drift detection, balanced-presentation verification, and crisis-screening pickup; institutional malpractice and research-liability coverage review.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    180[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    181[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Recruitment-pool diversity is the equity metric.** The bot's success in expanding the diversity of the engaged candidate pool, relative to the trial's target population and the institution's patient mix, is the equity metric. Per-cohort engagement, pre-screening, and handoff-completion rates are monitored explicitly.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    182[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    183[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Where the Field Has Moved
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    184[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    185[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A few practical updates worth knowing.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    186[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    187[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Industry-funded clinical-trial-matching platforms exist at scale.** Several commercial vendors offer trial-matching platforms that combine chart-data-driven pre-screening, patient-facing engagement, and coordinator-handoff. <!-- TODO: verify; the digital-trial-recruitment landscape includes platforms from TrialSpark, Antidote, Deep 6 AI, Mendel, ClinicalConnection, and others; specific product positioning and evidence varies --> Many institutions deploy a combination of an institutional bot for institution-managed trials and a vendor platform for the broader trial landscape.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    188[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    189[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **EHR-integrated chart-screening tools have matured.** Tools that run institutional patient data against trial-criteria libraries are mature enough to produce coordinator-actionable candidate lists, though false-positive rates and data-completeness gaps remain meaningful. The bot's conversation augments rather than replaces the chart-screening tool.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    190[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    191[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Decentralized clinical trials increase the bot's role.** Trials with remote-monitoring, at-home visits, and digital-data-collection components rely more heavily on digital recruitment, with the bot's conversational interface playing a larger role than in traditional site-based trials. <!-- TODO: verify; decentralized clinical trials, sometimes called DCTs, have grown substantially since the COVID-19 pandemic with FDA guidance on the topic; specific adoption patterns vary -->
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    192[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    193[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **ClinicalTrials.gov remains the U.S. registry standard.** ClinicalTrials.gov, operated by the U.S. National Library of Medicine, is the dominant U.S. trial registry, with mandatory listing for most FDA-regulated trials. <!-- TODO: verify; ClinicalTrials.gov listing requirements are specified in FDAAA Section 801 (42 USC 282(j)) and FDA regulations at 42 CFR Part 11; specific obligations vary --> Many institutional-bot deployments integrate with ClinicalTrials.gov as a content source for non-institutional trials.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    194[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    195[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Tool-using LLMs handle structured pre-screening and content delivery well when grounded carefully.** The function-calling pattern from the previous chapter 11 recipes maps to trial recruitment. The LLM produces tool calls that retrieve trial materials, run pre-screening, surface logistics, propose handoff, and post events for downstream operations.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    196[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    197[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Hybrid AI-plus-research-coordinator deployment is the dominant pattern in evidence-based products.** AI for candidate engagement, structured pre-screening, plain-language explanation, and warm handoff; research coordinators for formal eligibility evaluation, consent, enrollment, and ongoing study operations.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    198[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    199[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Equity in research is an active regulatory and policy concern.** FDA, NIH, and the broader research community have produced policies and guidance promoting diverse and equitable participation in clinical research. <!-- TODO: verify; FDA guidance includes the FDA Diversity Plans guidance from 2022 and related actions; NIH policies include the NIH Inclusion Across the Lifespan policy and the Clinical Trial Diversity policy; specific obligations vary --> Per-cohort monitoring with equity focus is essential.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    200[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    201[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Build-vs-buy is mature for most institutional contexts.** Most major institutions deploying in this space run a hybrid: build a thin institutional-bot orchestration layer in-house, partner with vendors for chart-screening and broader trial-landscape coverage, integrate with the institution's EHR and research-operations infrastructure.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    202[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    203[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    204[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[K
